*   **`allow_url_include%3d1`**: This decodes to `allow_url_include=1`. This is a PHP directive that, when set to `1` (or `On`), permits PHP's `include`, `require`, `include_once`, and `require_once` functions to include files from remote URLs. This setting is crucial for the remote code execution part of the exploit.
*   **`auto_prepend_file%3dphp://input`**: This decodes to `auto_prepend_file=php://input`. `auto_prepend_file` is a PHP directive that specifies a file to be automatically included before the main script is executed. `php://input` is a read-only stream that provides access to the raw data in the request body of a POST request. By injecting this directive, an attacker can send malicious PHP code directly in the POST request body, which the vulnerable server will then automatically execute.

In essence, the entire string, when used in a crafted HTTP POST request to a vulnerable server, leverages the Unicode character handling flaw to inject PHP configuration directives. These directives enable the inclusion of remote files and instruct PHP to execute code provided in the request body, leading to remote code execution.

